Amend addEntry method to insert entry according to order of date
commitResults.messageBody:
App stores and lists entries in order of time of entering event.
It would be more user-friendly if it stored and listed all entries
by ascending order of date of entry.

Let's amend the add entry function to always insert entries by order of
date.

We continue to use an ArrayList for the financial list to minimise
changes required in other parts of the code. The method checks whether
to insert entries from the end of the ArrayList as it is more likely
for users to add entries in ascending order of date, thus this should
reduce the average time needed to find the correct index to insert the
Financial entry.

Fix List Entries commands to include entries on start/end date
commitResults.messageBody:
App does not include entries which have the same date as the start/end
date specified when calling the list command. This is not intuitive
for the user.

Let's amend the commands such that when listing the financial entries,
entries which fall on the entered start/end date will also be listed.

Furthermore, the conditional to check if an entry falls within the
specified date range was extracted to a new method in
SeeAllEntriesCommands to improve code readability. Furthermore, this
method was set to protected to allow inheritance by
SeeAllExpensesCommand and SeeAllIncomesCommand, thus reducing
repeated code.

Edit EditEntryCommand to fix bug where edit changes order unnecessarily
commitResults.messageBody:
Edit command currently deletes the entry at the specified index and
adds a replacement entry to the list. This leads to the order of the
entry changing in the list even if there is no change in date, which
could throw users off.

Let's:
* Modify EditEntryCommand to increment/decrement the index of the
entry from its original index until it is correctly sorted in the
Financial List.

This prevents unnecessary changes in order of entries in the list.

commitResults.messageBody: This commit updates the implementation and documentation of the Storage class. The Storage class is responsible for storing the FinancialList into a file and restoring users' progress even if they have terminated the program. The update includes overriding the data/FinancialList.txt file with the up-to-date FinancialList converted to a string. Additionally, the commit clarifies the storage format of an Expense or Income, highlighting the differences between the format generated by the toString() method for CLS display and the toStorageString() method. It also adds an example of the storage format for an Income entry. The commit ensures that if the data/FinancialList.txt file doesn't exist, the program will generate one. Finally, the commit updates the glossary with relevant terms related to the FinancialEntry, description, amount, date, Expense, Income, and FinancialList.
